         <head>NOTES <hi rend="small">TO THE </hi> POEM <hi rend="small">OF</hi>
              MICHAEL.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <hi rend="small">note i. </hi>
         </head>
         <div xml:id="note1m">
            <p rend="note">Page 224—line 6. “There’s Richard Bateman,”
              &amp;c. The <lb/>story alluded to here is well known in the country. The <lb/>chapel
              is called Ings Chapel; and is on the right hand side <lb/>of the road leading from
              Kendal to Ambleside.</p>
         </div>
         <div xml:id="note2m">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">note ii.</hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note">Page 227—line 15. “——had designed to build a
              sheep-<lb/>fold.” &amp;c. It may be proper to inform some readers, that <lb/>a
              sheep-fold in these mountains is an unroofed building of <lb/>stone walls, with
              different divisions. It is generally placed <lb/>by the side of a brook, for the
              convenience of washing the <lb/>sheep; but it is also useful as a shelter for them,
              and as a <lb/>place to drive them into, to enable the shepherds conveni-<lb/>ently to
              single out one or more for any particular purpose.</p>
         </div>
         <trailer>
            <hi rend="small">THE END.</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <emph>R. Taylor and Co. Printers,</emph>
            38, <emph>Shoe-Lane.</emph>
